ice,\" replied Mr. Baker.\nOn farther questioning by Senator\nTf?lsh the witness said that this advice\nvas given him by Aionzo Tweedale,\nC\" eral controller of the Shipping\nid. i\nCharges for docking steamships in\nNew York were characterized as exorbi- i\ntait by Captain O. W. Parker, marine\ntoperintendent here for the Shipping\nJoard, in testimony before the com- j\nuiitter. Captain Parker toid the com-\nmittee that the state rented piers to\nprivate companies at a- very low cost\nand the leasors obtained from ship\neoBpanie? what they pleased.\nHigh Docking Charges\nThe state rate for docking ships, the\n?fUness said, was two cents a net\ntel for the first 200 tons ahd one and\na half cents a ton thereafter. The wit?\nness mentioned the case of one vessel\nm --?hich the dockage charges for one\nday by a private concern was ?180.\nThis he said was $140 in excels of the\nstate rat'\\ The witness advocated,\ngovernment operation, at least to the\nextent of having captains and engin?\neers in the pay of the government on\nboard its own ships to protect prop?\nerty, in preference to the bareboat\ncharter plan.\nOther witnesses yesterday included\nJohn U. Pigot, formerly a checker for\nthe Shipping Board in local shipyards.\nP%ot told of alleged threats against\nShipping Board checkers by men in the\nysW, but said the only act of violence\nh*know of was when he was \"beat up\"\non;the streets of Brooklyn. He said he\ncoWd never discover who his assailants\nChecker round Dead\nfie related one instance in which a\nemeker was found dead Ln the hold of\n.?hip. It developed, however, that\nthji man's death was accidental and\nWCtained no element of foul play.\n?bree members of a sub-committee\n?ft? Congressional select committee or.\nTOT Department expenditures met at\ntls? Pennsylvania Hotel yesterday to\nemmi-ie several witnesoes regarding\n?a award made for the reconditioning\net rest?is chartered by the War De\n?ptrtment during the war. The sub\n??mittee members are Representative\n??sea A. Frear, of Wisconsin; Albert\nJefferis, of Nebraska, and Clarence\nLea, of California. The only wit\nM*? examined was Captain T. L.\nWjPran, of the Judge Advocate's De\n?sytment, who described in detail and\nlamented report? regarding the requi\n??ouing of ships.\nwh the Walsh committee and the\n2**e*>n> mittee will reconvene thh\n\"?\"?mg at the Pennsylvania Hot?!.\nPenrose Reports Tariff\nBill; Seeks Early Action\n?^kate on Measure and Ten\nAmendments Expected to\nBe-gin Late This Week\nWASHINGTON. Jan. 17.?The Houae\n5J^*^ tariff bill, a? amended by\nt- ?v:?t.nc* Commute??, was presented\n?to? senate to-day by Senator Pen\ntrie committee chairman, who\nFW?s?<i that he scon would make\njp effort to press it to early past-,\nafc ?\"Jorny report of the eorn\nrg**' Senator P%nro?e did not pre\n?F ?07 arguments in behalf of the\nnor m support of the ten amend\n\"?g** approved by the committee,\n-fator Simmor... of North Caro\n?5> rankirig Democrat on the com\n?We*, ??id [.g ot fije a f0rrnjl;\n22*Ti.t7 report, erring to allow\n'\"^?tiont to U d?v?doped in debate,\nmm ?s exp9cUd to begin late this\n??ei\n%ody of Czar's Daughter\nfytiwt-d Hound to Egypt\nLlPn)0K? J\"*n- ''?Bodies suppose^\n7-^- t}\">?? of Grand Duchea? Olga,\n????bt'ir of former Emperor Nicholas\nJ**?**?*?, and her maid, are aboard\n79*rM?nn tu-we Devanh?, which is\nrf w> hlirypt at the end of th?\nr?*?f<t week. Disinterred at Yekater\nJJJ?'?; tj? S?odie-i are ?aid to have baan\nr\"?8-*d throogh Ferai? and tbence\n?w *??r?g*\".al.\nJit**- the armaj of the ?taamer they\n2? b? ?ia?rr,'r>ark*d and Uken to the\nI/'\"\" !r-t*-\"n?'rit\n**J*?nk M*m*n%*r of $2,000\n^fcOlT. Ja;;. 11. Automobil,\nS*\"-??? WA np h mes?enger Ut th?\n'?nd p?rk trUu Bat?, ia High\n^n?, V\"t. ?t?burb. late to-day and\njJJJ* Wit;' ?atrbe! containing ?bout\n2*y? MlniJte7\"|irierIin\n^WUi?an. 1?.-Kki H?oki. tb? r??\n^fK-mia? Japan??? Aoibaaaador\n\"TT# aMved io Bertio to?d?f'.\nAssurance of Payment\nSpeculators perhaps have made more\nmoney in investing in other things than in\nGuaranteed .Mortgages, but they also make\nheavy losses in them.\nNo one ha? made any losses in mort?\ngages guaranteed by the Bond Mortgage\nrua-r?ntee Company. ?r foreclosure is\nnecessary, he gets his interest reguHfrly\nmeantime and the guarantor buys in the\nropcrty and pays him his money in full*.\nBond Mortgage Guarantee Co.\n1 7 Broadway, New York City\n7i> Kcmsen Street, Brooklyn\nPacker? Blame\nWilson for Blow\nAI Foreign 1 Vacie\nCirculai ion o?' .Commission\nReport ou \"\"Big FiVe\" In?\nquiry Said lu Have In\nspired British Action\nWASHINGTON, Jan. 17.--?The alten--j\nlion of members of Congress v/a3 called\nby the Institute of American Meat\nPackers, through its Washington office,\nto proposals submitted to the British\nParliament regarding the meat industry\nand said to be designed to restrain\nAmerican packer.* from i'.urtber ex?\ntending their world trade.\nThe institute, in an c alter t:\nSenators; and Repr?sentative trans?\nmitting copies of a report so Parlia\na subcommittee of the stand?\ning committee on trusts, says this re?\nport was s1. consequence of the deliber?\nate circulation in foreign countries by\nthe Federal Trade Commission of the\ncommission's report on its investiga?\ntion of the '-Big Five\" packers, con?\nducted severa! year3 ago by direction\nof President Wilson.\nIt it* charged by the institute that\nthe trade commission not only fur\nnished copies of its report to repre?\nsentatives here of foreign governments,\nbut also asked the diplomatic bureau\nof the State Department to transmit\ncopies of the report direct to those\ngovernments.\nForeign Cooperation Sought\nThe commission, it is charged fur?\nther, sent to the diplomatic bureau a\nform letter to be used in transmitting\nthe report, which said:\n\"There is enclosed herewith a copy\nof the summary of the report of the\nFederal Trade Commission on the meat\nindustry which was recently released\nfor publication by President Wilson\nj and which may be of interest to your\ngovernment.\"\n\"By this form letter,*\" says the insti\ni tute's communication, \"President Wil\nI son was made to extend the invitation\nj to foreign governments to take the\nj fundamental action which the commis?\nsion said was necessary to prevent in\nI ternationai control of meat .products\nj by the American packers.\"\nThe institute's letter goes on to say\nI that members of Congress after read\ning*> .the British committee's report\nwhich quotes at great length from ??he\ni trade commission report, \"will appre\nciate the seriou? disaster which threat\nj ens the livestock industry of thia coun\nI try as a consequence of the deliberate\ncirculation in foreign countries by the\nFederal Trade Commission of its fais?\nand unjust charges against the Ameri\nI can packers.\" _\nMalbone Cases Are Dropped\ni Indictments Against Dempse)\nand Others Dismissed\nIndictments against former official;\nj of the Brooklyn Rapid Transit Com\npany, growing out of the Malbone\nStreet tunnel disaster on November 1\n1918, were dismissed yesterday ii\nj Mine?la by Justice Edward Lazansky\nof the Supreme Court. Some of- th<\ni officials, all of whom were indicted fo:\nmanslaughter, were charged specifi\ncally with responsibility for the deatl\nI of Thoma3 F. Gilfeather and some fo:\nthat of Edward Erskine Porter.\nThe officials under indictment wen\nI Timothy S. Williams, former presiden\ni of the company; John Dempsey, forme\ngeneral superintendent of transporta\ntion; John II. Hallock, Thomas F\nBlewitt, division superintendent, am\nWilliam S. Menden, chief engineer\nj The motorman of the ill-fated trail\nwas also named, in the indictmenu\nSeveral of the cases were tried an?\nthe officials acquitted.\nHere's a Russian\nViolinist Who Fails\nTo Use First Name\nBail Mitnitzky, in Other\nRespects, Is Not Unlike\nOther? oi* His Countrymen\nVisiting U. S. This? Season\nTh? record Is hopelessly confused,\nso it cannot be stated with accuracy I\n.'t -,i 'a? tzi- i.. w n z c a rec:?:?-\narnegie Hall last night, was the\nfifteenth or twentieth Russian vioiir.-\nist who came to seek a fortune in I\nthe United States this 3easoi;, nor!\nu,m... il matter. tic <_oc? not differ\nmaterially .';-'j..; tho majority of his\noi in his qualifications und!\n'orhaps unessential tnat ho doea\nnot cail himself Sascha, Mischa, Jas-\ncha cv i-Jeseha, but leaves his first]\nname to speculation.\nrlc is also older, apparently, and\nmoro seasoned than the majority of\nhis recent predecessors, though he does\nnot yet seem to have developed a\nstyle wiiich might be characterized as\nhaving distinction. To judge by the first\nnumber on his program, Vitali's Cia\nconna, he conceives that a dry, un?\nyielding and angular manner is es?\nsential to the old Italian ?lassies, and\nthat they allow of much sliding about\non the fingerboard; which is deplor?\nable.\nHis Mozart concerto (that in D)\nwas better in conception than in execu?\ntion, for while it was evident that he\naimed at ??race it -was al30 obvious that\nhe did not attain that desirable qual?\nity.\nBut the fact will soon have to be\nconfessed by reviewers that they have\nheard so much fairly good violin play?\ning of late that only an extraordinary\ngenius, a much greater one than this\nseason has produced, will meet with\ntheir entire approbation.\n\nPalace Bill Good Despite\nFaulty Blinn Production\nCondensed French Farce Falls\nBelow Standard, hut Other\nActs Redeem Program\nA variety bill of interesting acts is\npresented at the Palace Theater this\nweek. Jame3 Burke and Eleanor Dur\nkin, appearing on the stage for the\nfirst time, made firm friends at once\nwith Palace patrons with their \"Tete-a\nTete in Song.\" Miss Durkin has\nbeauty, an excellent voice and a per?\nsonality that wins. Mr. Burke also is\nan able comediar?.\nHolbrook Blinn's production of a\nFrench farce entitled \"The Bride,\" used\nas a vehicle for Lina Abarbanell, is a\ndisappointment. In humorous content j\nand moral quality it is much below the\nstandard of the Palace. It3 theme is\nmore sordid than funny?that of the\nmarried woman who entertains a multi?\nplicity of lovers and contrives upon\nher husband's sudden homecoming to\nhave them taken as burglars and re?\nlieved of the jewels they had brought,\nHer character is frankly that of a\n\"gold digger,\" not an Anne Page, of\n\"The Merry Wives of Windsor.\" It is\non old piece freshened only by a song\nwhich Miss Abarbanell sing3 pleasingly\nenough.\nBut there ia abundant material to re?\ndeem the bill. Beth Beri, a California\nartist, did some dances that have sel?\ndom been surpassed here in the music\nhall. George M. Ro6en?r gave a se?\nries of character studies. Ed. Gallag?\nher and Joe Rolley, Robert Emmet\ni Keane, Adelaide and Hughes, the Four\nKassams and Mme. Hermann, widow of\ni the magician, are on the program.\nCamparter>]Knct l8to)E9B?35\nMerman C*\n1 AND 3 WEST 37TH ST.\n?MB DODI mom rirtH ?rsNoi\nLACE CURTAINS\nAT\n10%*DISCOUNT\nFROM PRICES that are now and have been\nmuch below the regular market prices, thus\naffording a VERY SUBSTANTIAL SAVING\nSize?, 2%, 3% &4 yds. long.\nBrussels Sash Curtains,\n27 in. wide, 3 yds. long,\n$15 to $65.\nBr?ssels Long Curtains,\n50 in. wide, 3?/2 and 4\nyds. long, $20 to $115.\nLacet Arabe Sash Cur?\ntains, 27 in. wide, 2?/2\nand 3 yds. long, $13.50\nto $32.\nLacet Arabe Long Cur?\ntains, 50 in. wide, 3</2\nand 4 yds. long, $25 to\n$125.\nFicelle Sash Curtains, 27 in. wide,\n3 yds. long, $5.75 to $16.50\nFicelle Curtains, 45 in. wide, 2Vi,\n3 and 3?/2 yds. long, $8.50 to $17.50\nMarquisette, Grenadine and Etamine Cur?\ntains?Made in our own Workrooms, made\nwith Hem and Edge, also Insertion and Edge,\n40 In. wide, 2 </2 and 3 yds. long, $2.25 to $15 Pair.\nODD PAIRS OF CURTAINS and REMNANTS\naf<5ibb0ttibi CiuiUlt\nBankers Told\nEurope Needs\nLong Credits\nGovernor Harding Advises\nAid to Prevent Piling!\nUp of Products Nations\nNo Longer Can Pay Forj\nFalse Prophets Assailed\n\nCharles? H. Sabin Denounces\nthe Rumor Mongers as)\nFoes of Trade Revival;\nGovernor V?*. P. G. Harding, of the I\nFederal Reserve Board, speaking last\nnight at a dinner of the New York!\nState Bankers' Association at the Wal- I\ndorf-Astoria, said both long term\ncredits and investments in European i\nsecurities were needed to supplement\nordinary banking activities in effect?\ning the financial rehabilitation of for?\neign countries.\nThe dinner was attended by 300,\nprominent bankers. Charles H. Sabin,\npresident of the Guaranty Trust Com- j\npany, was another speaker.\nThe subject of Governor Harding's\ntalk was \"Working Back ?.o Normal.\"\nHe declared that good limes were\nahead for the United States and said j\na bright futuro would be the reward\nof hard and intelligent work. Produc?\ntion, he said, must continue if the\ncountry was to prosper. He stressed!\nthe importance of a continuance of\ntrade with Europe, and said ths\nmaintenance of trade relationships of\nother countries with Europe was j\nscarcely less important.\nGlut of Products Feared\n'Otherwise, there will be a constant\ntendency.'' the Governor explained, \"to- i\nward the accumulation here or' goods,\nprincipally raw materials, from those\ncountries which have been in the habit\nof selling to Europe, but which now,\non account of Europe's inability to pay\nand their own inability to extend credit,\nare shipping to the Uunited-States.\n\"The War Finance Corporation has\nbeen revised,\" he added, \"and, subject\nto the act creating it, it is authorized\nto extend credits in export transac?\ntions, but it is evident that new agen?\ncies must be resorted to in order to\nfurnish Europe with long-time credit,\nwhich is so essential for her rehabilita-\ntion and for hei continuance as a\npotential buyer in the world's mar?\nkets.\"'\nMr. Sabin in his address declared\nthat the United States, together with\nother nations, needed stabilization of\nmind more than stabilization of prices\nand economic conditions.\nFalse Prophets Condemned\n\"It is time for us.\" he said, \"to turn\nfrom these false prophets who have\ninflicted their fallacious theories upon\na suffering world, willing, in its\nmisery, to try any alleged cure for\neconomic and political ills. It is time\nfor us to turn a deaf ear to pessimists\nand rumor mongers, whose thought?\nlessness or maliciousness is frequently\nas dangerous and criminal as it is un?\njust and unwarranted.\n\"Such perverted talking and loose\nthinking as have ruined a great state\nlike Russia are now .seeking to injure\nour private and public institutions and\nare striving to undermine our national\nConstitution and form of government.\nThey are productive of such a das?\ntardly assault upon life and property\nas was made a few months ago in the\nheart of the financial district. They\nare responsible to-day for the utterly\nfalse and absurd rumors surreptitiously\ncirculated about solvent firms and\nsound financial institutions.\"\nMr. Sabin asserted there was rea?\nsonable assurance of a return to nor?\nmal business conditions, stabilized\nprices, easier money and larger busi?\nness opportunities during the coming\nyear.\nr\nTwo Plead Guilty to\nDefrauding Wounded\nFormer Examiners in War Risk\nBureau May Get Four Years\nin Penitentiary\nWASHINGTON. Jan. 17.?William F.\n?Salisbury jr., of Buffalo, and David M. j\n3riswold, of Brooklyn, pleaded guilty\n:o-day in the District of Columbia\nsupreme Court to two indictments in\n?onnection with the war risk insurance\n\"rauds by which a number of wounded\nwar veterans were mulcted of large\n?urns to expedite their claims against\n;he government.\nThe pair were examiners of claims\n;n the bureau and were charged with\nsaving furnished information of claims\nabout to be allowed and having had\nothers interview the prospective claim?\nants and arrange with them for a divi?\nsion of the awards. As much as 50 per\ncent of the ciaima was demanded in\nsome cases, the ??overiinient contended.\nJustice Gould set no date for the\nsentence, the men being at liberty un?\nder bail. The maximum penalty under\neach 01 the indictments is two years\nin the penitentiary and a fine o?'\n$10,000. The men may be sent to the\npenitentiary for a total of four years,\nin addition to a fine not to excee?i\n$20,000.\nSeveral other persons outside the\nwar risk insurance bureau have been\nindicted individually and jointly with\nSalisbury and Grisvvold and have en?\ntered pleas of not guilty.\nThieves Get $27,500\nin Two Ohio Banks\n15 Out of 50 Safety Deposit\nBoxes Looted of Liberty\nBonds\nWARREN, Ohio, Jan. 17.-Liberty\nbonds and Thrift stamps estimated ai\n$25,000 were stolen by robbers, wht\nbroke into the North Bloonitleld Bank?\ning Company's bank at North Bloom\nfield, twelve miles from here, last night\nand rifled forty-five out of fifty safetj\ndeposit boxes.\nPAINESVILLE, Ohio, Jan. 17.?Tw\nrobbers this afternoon entered the Wes\nMentor Building and Loan Company'\nbank at West Mentor, eight miles wes\nof here, bound and gagged Cashier E\nF. Sawyer, ransacked the place am\nescaped in an automobile with mone,\nestimated at $2,500.\nSheriff Spink and a posse in auto\nmobiles are in pursuit.\n\nDr. Silverman Retired\nWith $12,000 a Yea\nBecomes Rabbi Emeritus Afte\nMeeting in Whicb Congrega?\ntion Pensions Him for Life\nDr. Joseph Silverman, who resigne\nas rabbi of Temple Emanu-El in Decer\nber, was made a rabbi emeritus for lii\non a pension of $12,000 a year by a vo\nof the board of trustees and congreg.\ntion last night. Dr. Silverman's resi\nnation was accepted in a resolution\nwhich esteem for him and gratitu?\nfor his service were expressed.\n\"As habbi emeritus,\" explained Lou\nMarshall, president of the board\ntrustees, \"Dr. Silverman will only\ncalled upon to exercise those rabbi\nical functions which he wishes to pc\nform, or upon occasions when t\ncongregation or _ the board especia!\nrequests his assistance.\"\n\nAllied Bankers Advance Fund\nTo China for Famine Reli\nPEKING, Jan. 17.?A loan of 4,00\n000 taels by American, British, Fren\nand Japanese banks, to be applied\nthe relief of famine-stricken distric\nhas been concluded by the Minisl\nof Finance with the approval of dip\nmat% assigned to the Chinese repub]\nThe loan will be secured by a a\ntoms surtax amounting to 10 per ce\nthe date of the application of whi\nhas not been fixed.\n\"The Createsl\nTreasure House\nof Linens\n<n America\"\nReg. Trado Mark\nm\nJanuary Sale\nof Household Linens\nReductions of 15% to 33Vz%\nThese reductions cover all of our\nHousehold Linen Departments.\nIncluded are:\nTOWELS\nDAMASK TABLE LINENS\nBLANKETS and BED LINENS\nFANCY LINENS\nand\nCOMFORTABLES\nJames McCutcheon Co.\nFifth Ave., 34th and 33d Streets\nflWWWIWWBfMfffWMiMlfflffllWWBBWirf'\n\"Economy is Thrift\"\nEconomize?be thrifty?save!\nThink it?plan it?act it!\nIf you have a good position hold on to it.\nIf you are unemployed make every effort to get busy and\nkeep busy.\nThe New York Tribune has frequently been the means of\naiding young men and women to secure steady positions.\nMany successful business people can trace their start to The\nTribune's Help and Situation Wanted Ad Columns.\nConsult The Tribune's Help Wanted Columns, and if the\nposition you seek Is not advertised put a Situation Wanted\nAd in to-morrow's Tribune?25c for 12 words and 20c for each\nadditional line of 6 words. Bring or mail it with your remit?\ntance to The Tribune Office, 154 Nassau Street, or go to any\nof The Tribune's Want Ad Agencies, conveniently located in\nall parts of Greater New York, at newsdealer, stationery and\ncigar stores, etc,\n-.-.-.-nr\n_ADVERTISEMENT ADVERTISEMENT__L ADVERTISEMENT\nA BUSINESS MESSAGE;\nThe Buyers' Strike\nThrift vs. Spending\nThis is addressed especially to the\nRetail Merchants, but we hope every?\nbody will read it. This is National\nThrift Week, and hundreds of men and\nwomen are earnestly at work and want\nas many more as possible to help them.\nThrift does not mean hoarding, but\nmeans wise spending either for the com?\nforts of life or insurance or. bank re?\nserves or investing. On Monday I re?\nceived the following letter:\nJanuary 17. 1921\nMr. Henrv L. Doherty,\n60 Wall Street,\nNew York City.\nDear Mr. Doherty:\nIt has been brought to our attention that\nsome of the retail merchants are not in\nsympathy with a Thrift Movement at this\ntime, believing it will be harmful to their\nbusiness. We are asking a number of our\nspeakers to assure the merchants that we\ndo not want to hurt their business, bu\nwant to help. Will you please do what\nyou can to help us promptly correct thl?\nmatter?\nLet me suggest that you take this up\nin your talk at the Brooklyn Central\nBranch of the Y. M. C. A.'to-night, and\nperhaps you would be willing to ?nswe\nthis matter through the press by interview\nor in your own advertising ?pace.\nVery truly yours,\n(Sd.) W. H. BAXLEY, Secretary.\nNew York City Thrift Committee\nThis appeals to me as a vastly impor\ntant matter, for we want the support of\nthese merchants, and as v/e are already\nin the Campaign and as we can reach so\nfew people with our voices, I am glad to\npay for the necessary space in the daily\npapers to say a little bit of the much we\nrnight say about what we hope to accom?\nplish.\nAll of us who are whole-heartedly\nsupporting the Thrift movement believe\nit is not only helpful to business, but\nabsolutely necessary for business.\nAs a portion of Thrift Week is al\nready gone, we cannot get together and\nharmonize our differences of opinion:\nso the only thing left for us to do is tc\nuse space in the daily papers to present\nour views and invite those who dissent\nto present their views frankly and in a\nlike manner.\nWe believe that Thrift, and Invest?\nment is at all times helpful to business\nand that it is particularly needed just\nnow. Our non-sympathizers, we under?\nstand, think Thrift, and Investment is\ngenerally a good thing, but that just now\nit will accentuate the so-called Buyers'\nStrike.\nSome merchants seem to think that an\nAmerican Federation of Retail Buyers\nhas sprung up over night which in\nstrength and determination is equal tc\nthe American Federation of Labor, and\nthat the first thing the new Federation\ndid was to declare a Buyers' Strike.\nThere is no more of a \"Buyers' Strike'\namong the retail buyers than there is a\nBuyers' Strike on the part of the retail\nmerchants themselves. Don't you think\nthat figures would show that the public\nis buying more from the retail merchant\nthan the retail merchant is buying from\nthe jobber and the manufacturer? How\nmany retail merchants do you think arr,\nwilling to take the money their retail\ncustomer pays them and pass the proper\nshare of it right along to the jobber and\nto the factory for more goods?\nHow many merchants do you think are\nalready carrying less than normai\nstocks??and how many do you think of\nthose who are carrying normal or abnor\nmay stocks would resist the temptation\nto reduce their stocks far below normal\nif they could create enough retail buying\nto enable them to do so?\nNow, we have all seen some wonder?\nfully clever advertisements tellirig why\nthe people should buy merchandise lib?\nerally. I hope every merchant who is\nnot in sympathy with the National\nThrift Drive will get these advertise?\nments and read them over and make Uij\nhis mind how much of the advice giver\nto the retail buyer he will accept for\nhimself and how much of this advice he\nthinks his fellow merchant will accept.\nLet me remind you that our presert\ntroubles were brought on largely by\nwild and extravagant buying on the part\nof the public. Retail merchants were\nencouraged to place abnormally large\norders to insure against depletion of\nstocks and rely on their banks to carry\nthem. This, with the load the bank,\nwere already carrying, brought a strain\non our banking system which carried it\ntc its full elastic limit. Money there?\nafter had to be rationed. The public i'i\nt\nmc tgnt until they n >n:\nover-stocked and the retail merchants in\nother cases bought until they had become\nover-stocked.\nThe retail customer does not buy in\ngreater volume, first, because the man\nout of employment is not apt to have he\nmoney or credit with which to buy, and .J!\nthe man who is still employed sees wide?\nspread unemployment and wonders ho<v\nsecure his employment is; second, be?\ncause a large portion of the public think\nwe are going to have still lower price-?.\nNow, some of the retail merchants do\nnot buy, first, because they fear that the\nbusiness depression has become so wide?\nspread that the future purchasing power\nof the American people has been ser<\nously crippled; second, because they\nfear still lower prices; and, third, be?\ncause they are having difficulty in rats\ning the money necessary to pay thei\nobligations when they come due.\nThere is nothing irt the National\nThrift movement which opposes jud' \"^TT\ncious or conservative buying. There u\nno reason v/hy the merchant should not\nstrive to stimulate buying, and there is\nno reason why he should not tell his cus?\ntomer that it is his belief that prices\nhave reached the bottom, if he really be?\nlieves it himself.\nBut, Mr. Merchant, let's be fair again.\nWe know prices have been abnormally\nhigh. We all hoped they would com-*\nback to normal in a gradual and crd'jr!;\nmanner?that they would evolute, no.\nrevolute; but when we reached the limi\nof our banking credit, and the bank-?'\"\nhad to call a halt, then, in many cases,\nfactories, jobbers and retailers had to\nsell some cf their goods for whatever\nthey would bring?and here and there\nsome commodities had to be sold at ic\":->\nthan the pre-war cost of production;\nNow, what do you '.hink is the greatest\nthreat of further demoralization of\nprices? think the greatest threat is to\nhave further forced sales. Don't forget\nthat many and, in fact, most cf these\nforced sales were not due to lack of capi\nral, but due to lack of cash. Don't ?01\nget, either, that there are still many fac\nlories, jobbers and retailers who are still\nunder a great strain, and although they\nhave an abundance of capital, yet they\n::re finding it difficult to find the cash c\nmeet their obligations.\nThose of us who are supporting thi<5\nNational Thrift movement believe th'-*1\nmoney applied to these strained situa\nrions will do more to help the mercantile\nsituation than a like amount cf money\napplied to indiscriminate buying. Illus-\ntrating perhaps by exaggeration, we feel\nthat if the man who has an appetite to\nsmoke a one dollar imported cigar would\ncontent himself with a ten cent domestic\ncigar, and would say to the soiuid mer?\nchant who is under a strain: \"Here is\nninety cents that I will loan you to help\nprevent you from being compelled tc\nmake a forced ?ale of your goods,\" we\nthink that this would aid the entire busi?\nness and mercantile situation more than\nif he had bought and snicked the oie\ndollar cigar. Now, we know that ninely\ncents would not help very much, and we\nknow that this man, and the man like\nhim, cannot deal direct with the mer?\nchant but all of these people can de?\nposit in some bank, which, in turn, will\nuse it to help out these particularly\nstrained business situations and prevent\nforced selling.\nI know a great many of the men who\narc working whole-heartedly behind this\nNational Thrift movement. Many of\nthem are merchants themselves. None of\nthem want to interfere with the business\nof our merchants, but to be helpful to\nthem. If we are wrong, you can tell the t\npeople why in the papers tomorrow. i\nThe foregoing letter is but little of\nwhat can be said in favor of support of\nthe National Thrift movement, but if\nwhat has already been said sounds rea?\nsonable, then take a chance and get be?\nhind the National Thrift Drive wich\nyour whole heart in it. Give the pubh'c\nthe assurance that the business men of\nthe country are fully cognizant of the\nsituation, that they are not fearful about\nit and will not themselves \"hunt cover,\"\nand that they mean to correct the situ?\nation as rapidly as circumstances will\npermit, and you will change the mind of T'.\nthe retail buyer over night.\nConservative buying will again start\nup and the buyer will pay what price he\nmust whether he thinks it is the bottom\nprice or not, and more will be accom?\nplished than by any attempt to break up\nthe so-called buyers' strike,\nThursday, if I am not called upon to\nmake further reply along this line, I will\ntell you some of the reasons why I am a\ndecided optimist on the business outlook\nprovided the employers will get behi* d\na Thrift and Investment Movement and\ntry to show why wise investing is in\nruth wise spending and will help moro\n..han the expenditure which buys some\nthing winch is consumed.\nFaithfully yours,\nHENRY L. DOHERTY,\nWall Street* New York,","height":"25203","width":"19752"}}
